threats.title: Developer commits secret to Git
threats.description: A developer commits secrets to version control either accidentally or on purpose. An angry employee with read access to the repository finds the secrets and proceeds to use them to steal end-user data
threats.mitigation:
Use .gitignore to avoid committing sensitive files.
Scan commits for secrets using tools like GitGuardian or TruffleHog.
Store secrets in secure vaults instead of code.
Train developers to follow secure coding practices.

threats.title: Compromised CI Pipeline Executor
threats.description: An attacker exploits a vulnerability in the pipeline executor to gain unauthorized privileges or execute arbitrary commands.
threats.mitigation:
Run jobs with least privilege and isolated containers (e.g., Kubernetes or Docker sandboxing).
Patch and update CI tools regularly.
Enforce RBAC (Role-Based Access Control).

threats.title: Security Gate Bypassed
threats.description: Vulnerabilities are not scanned or flagged due to misconfigured or bypassed security gate controls.
threats.mitigation:
Enforce automated security scans as a blocking step.
Regularly validate and test pipeline configurations.
Use tools like OWASP ZAP or Snyk integrated into the CI process.

threats.title: Unauthorized Image Published to Dockerhub
threats.description: An image is built and pushed to Dockerhub without proper auditing or logging, possibly by an attacker.
threats.mitigation:
Enable image signing using cosign.
Maintain detailed audit logs of all build and push actions.
Use immutable tags and restrict access with write permissions.

threats.title: Unverified Dependencies Introduced
threats.description: Malicious or compromised third-party dependencies could be fetched and included in the build process, allowing backdoors or exploits.
threats.mitigation:
Use tools like Sigstore Cosign, SLSA, or JFrog Xray to verify package signatures.
Maintain an allowlist of approved libraries and versions.
Run Software Composition Analysis (SCA).

threats.title: Insider tampering with Sonarqube results
threats.description: A malicious insider manipulates code quality metrics or security scan results.
threats.mitigation:
Restrict access to analysis results.
Store reports in immutable storage or under version control.
Enable audit trails in Sonarqube and enforce multi-user approval for overriding results.
